 programs are cut, Madriz points out, those for more prisons and police are on the increase. She also illustrates how media images of victims—"good" victims aren't culpable, "bad" victims invite trouble—and a tough political stance toward criminals are linked to a general climate of economic uncertainty and conservatism.Madriz argues that fear itself is a strong element in keeping women in subservient and self-limiting social positions. "Policing" themselves, they construct a restricted world that leads to positions of even greater subordination: Being a woman means being vulnerable. Considering the enormous attention given to crime today, including victims' rights and use of public funds, Madriz's informative study is especially timely.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFear of crimexUnited States. 0aFear of crimezUnited States. 0aWomenxAttitudesxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aWomenxCrimes againstxUnited States. 0aWomenxCrimes againstzUnited States. 0aWomenxPsychologyxUnited States. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxAttitudes. 0aWomenzUnited StatesxPsychology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z978311063534840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520918962?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520918962423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520918962/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles